  "response_text": "# Exercises for Manual Labor-Based Back Pain\n\n## Movements that complement rather than duplicate your work\n\n**Counterbalancing repetitive postures:**\n- If you're bent forward (farming/weaving): gentle back extensions, reverse rows, prone cobra stretches\n- If you're twisted or asymmetrical: rotation stretches in both directions, pallof presses, cross-body movements\n- If you're overhead (harvesting): shoulder mobility work, gentle lat stretches\n\n**Functional strengthening:**\n- Loaded carries (mimics work but controlled)\n- Farmer's walks with even weight distribution\n- Dead bugs and bird dogs (core stability without heavy load)\n- Planks and side planks (brief, high quality)\n\n**Recovery-focused:**\n- Hip flexor stretches (counteracts prolonged sitting/bending)\n- Thoracic spine mobility (opens chest after hunched work)\n- Glute activation (often weak despite leg work)\n- Gentle spinal decompression stretches\n\n## Practical integration\n\n- **Timing matters**: Light stretching before work prevents stiffness; stronger work after\n- **Low equipment**: bodyweight and simple tools fit artisan/farming contexts\n- **Brief sessions**: 10-15 minutes prevents fatigue that worsens form\n- **Consistency beats intensity**: daily gentle work beats occasional hard sessions\n\n**Key principle**: Your work *is* exercise—the goal is balancing it, not replacing it.\n\nHave you noticed which specific movements or positions trigger your pain most?",
